  footnotes: []
english:
  title: In Reply to Judge Jeong's Letter
  author: Choi Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A mountain dweller writes: In the early days of this month, an official from the capital arrived bearing a letter, saying it was sent by the Inspector. I was startled and delighted, kneeling to receive it. Before even breaking the seal, a single sheet of noble writing gleamed before my eyes. Upon opening it, I beheld beautiful paper adorned with masterful brushwork—jeweled phrases and elegant language that blazed across the page. At first, like one dazzled by golden music from afar, I could barely comprehend it. Reading slowly, I found myself returning to it again and again. The words are keen and striking; the sentiments expressed are intricate yet complete. It was as though I stood myself in the Hall of Tranquility, facing a clear countenance and hearing words of purity. Now I truly understand: those of kindred spirit meet not through earthly dust, but through deeper communion.

    My former doubts—fears that wealth might corrupt the heart, hesitations about a hermit's path, anxieties about what I did not understand—all these melted away like ice in an instant. I see now that the insight of one who has penetrated truth surpasses even the ancient mirrors of emperors, revealing all without omission. The gratitude I feel runs too deep for words to capture.

    Your two poems arrived with language of such height, and the rhyme on the character "Xun" flows with particular force. I dare not take brush in hand to reply, and must humbly ask your generosity to forgive my silence. The heat persists; I reverently hope you will preserve yourself for the nation's sake, granting answer to my distant prayers.

    I cannot say all that fills my heart. In trembling respect, I bow twice.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a reply to a letter from Judge Jeong, likely a high official of the Goryeo court. The exchange reflects the Confucian ideal of learned men recognizing kindred spirits through correspondence.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Hall of Tranquility'' (無慍堂) appears to be a reference to a respected scholar''s study, possibly that of the addressee.'
  - key: ''
    value: The 'two poems' mentioned were compositions sent by Judge Jeong, which the author found so skillfully wrought that he felt compelled not to attempt a reply in verse.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Earthly dust'' is a Buddhist-influenced metaphor for the material world and its attachments.'
